results.notes:
More notes coming.

This mushroom was much more similar to the typical description of C. coccolobae than the previous find, though it’s possible they’re both the same species. I have made a collection of these to be dehydrated too.

Comparing to my previous sighting. ( https://mushroomobserver.org/541592 )
- Caps were more colorful, seemed a bit more damp to the touch.
- There were trees I believe were Coccoloba trees in the vicinity, and also some palm. Previous mushroom didn’t appear to be near Coccoloba trees. Though I can double check my photos to be sure.
- Soil was sandier here, and we were within eyeshot of the ocean.
- Stipe was beautifully colored, but more uniform. Not the full gradient of Red to Yellow, more a yellow-orange color.
- Raw taste was not spicy, or very mildly spicy. Cooked taste was delicious, not noticeably spicy, very similar to other chanterelle species I have eaten.
- Spore print was also pale/white.

results.notes:
Collected by Maggie Lutz during the West Virginia Mushroom Club’s 2023 foray. Growing on an unidentified hardwood chunk. Caps hygrophanous – “yellowish brown” (10YR 5/6 in Munsell) when wet or at margins, fading to whitish (“pale yellow” 2.5Y 8/2); dry; glabrous; infundibuliform; up to 21.9 mm wide. Gills “very pale yellow” (2.5Y 9.5/2), decurrent. Stems “very pale brown” (10YR 7/4) to “pale brown” (2.5Y 8/4, 2.5Y 7/4); innately fibrous; twisted; dry; with white basal mycelium and occasional white rhizoids; up to 20.4 mm long and 3.5 mm wide. Associated with a white mycelial mat. Cap and stem context white and solid. Spore print white. Odor and taste frainose. Not fluorescing under 365 nm UV light.
